  "prompt": "Does a degree from a lower ranked school decrease job prospects? Do employers not care where one graduated from as long as the school was accredited?",
  "response": "The importance of school ranking can vary depending on the industry, specific job, and employer. Here's a balanced perspective:\n\nFactors that matter:\n- Accreditation is often more important than specific ranking\n- Your skills, experience, and performance matter significantly\n- Networking and internships can be more impactful than school reputation\n- Some competitive fields (like tech, finance) may care more about school prestige\n\nWhere school ranking might matter more:\n- Very competitive industries (investment banking, top consulting)\n- First job out of college\n- Graduate school admissions\n- Certain high-profile companies with selective hiring\n\nWhere school ranking matters less:\n- Many technical and trade fields\n- Small to mid-size companies\n- Industries that value practical skills\n- Jobs that prioritize experience and performance\n\nTips to improve job prospects regardless of school:\n- Develop strong skills in your field\n- Build a robust portfolio\n- Network actively\n- Gain internships and practical experience\n- Consider certifications\n- Demonstrate achievements and initiative\n\nGeneral advice: While school ranking can provide some advantages, it's not the sole or even primary determinant of career success. Your individual capabilities, work ethic, and professional development are typically more important.",
